<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="NAME"
>NAME <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>XML::DOM - A perl module for building DOM Level 1 compliant document structures</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="SYNOPSIS"
>SYNOPSIS <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<pre class="sh_perl"> use XML::DOM;

 my $parser = new XML::DOM::Parser;
 my $doc = $parser-&#62;parsefile (&#34;file.xml&#34;);

 # print all HREF attributes of all CODEBASE elements
 my $nodes = $doc-&#62;getElementsByTagName (&#34;CODEBASE&#34;);
 my $n = $nodes-&#62;getLength;

 for (my $i = 0; $i &#60; $n; $i++)
 {
     my $node = $nodes-&#62;item ($i);
     my $href = $node-&#62;getAttributeNode (&#34;HREF&#34;);
     print $href-&#62;getValue . &#34;\n&#34;;
 }

 # Print doc file
 $doc-&#62;printToFile (&#34;out.xml&#34;);

 # Print to string
 print $doc-&#62;toString;

 # Avoid memory leaks - cleanup circular references for garbage collection
 $doc-&#62;dispose;</pre>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="DESCRIPTION"
>DESCRIPTION <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>This module extends the XML::Parser module by Clark Cooper. The XML::Parser module is built on top of XML::Parser::Expat, which is a lower level interface to James Clark&#39;s expat library.</p>

<p>XML::DOM::Parser is derived from XML::Parser. It parses XML strings or files and builds a data structure that conforms to the API of the Document Object Model as described at <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-DOM-Level-1" class="podlinkurl"
>http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-DOM-Level-1</a>. See the XML::Parser manpage for other available features of the XML::DOM::Parser class. Note that the &#39;Style&#39; property should not be used (it is set internally.)</p>

<p>The XML::Parser <i>NoExpand</i> option is more or less supported, in that it will generate EntityReference objects whenever an entity reference is encountered in character data. I&#39;m not sure how useful this is. Any comments are welcome.</p>

<p>As described in the synopsis, when you create an XML::DOM::Parser object, the parse and parsefile methods create an <i>XML::DOM::Document</i> object from the specified input. This Document object can then be examined, modified and written back out to a file or converted to a string.</p>

<p>When using XML::DOM with XML::Parser version 2.19 and up, setting the XML::DOM::Parser option <i>KeepCDATA</i> to 1 will store CDATASections in CDATASection nodes, instead of converting them to Text nodes. Subsequent CDATASection nodes will be merged into one. Let me know if this is a problem.</p>

<p>When using XML::Parser 2.27 and above, you can suppress expansion of parameter entity references (e.g. %pent;) in the DTD, by setting <i>ParseParamEnt</i> to 1 and <i>ExpandParamEnt</i> to 0. See <a href="#_Hidden_Nodes_" class="podlinkpod"
>Hidden Nodes</a> for details.</p>

<p>A Document has a tree structure consisting of <i>Node</i> objects. A Node may contain other nodes, depending on its type. A Document may have Element, Text, Comment, and CDATASection nodes. Element nodes may have Attr, Element, Text, Comment, and CDATASection nodes. The other nodes may not have any child nodes.</p>

<p>This module adds several node types that are not part of the DOM spec (yet.) These are: ElementDecl (for &#60;!ELEMENT ...&#62; declarations), AttlistDecl (for &#60;!ATTLIST ...&#62; declarations), XMLDecl (for &#60;?xml ...?&#62; declarations) and AttDef (for attribute definitions in an AttlistDecl.)</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="XML::DOM_Classes"
>XML::DOM Classes <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>The XML::DOM module stores XML documents in a tree structure with a root node of type XML::DOM::Document. Different nodes in tree represent different parts of the XML file. The DOM Level 1 Specification defines the following node types:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/Node.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::Node</a> - Super class of all node types</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/Document.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::Document</a> - The root of the XML document</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/DocumentType.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::DocumentType</a> - Describes the document structure: &#60;!DOCTYPE root [ ... ]&#62;</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/Element.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::Element</a> - An XML element: &#60;elem attr=&#34;val&#34;&#62; ... &#60;/elem&#62;</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/Attr.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::Attr</a> - An XML element attribute: name=&#34;value&#34;</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/CharacterData.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::CharacterData</a> - Super class of Text, Comment and CDATASection</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/Text.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::Text</a> - Text in an XML element</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/CDATASection.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::CDATASection</a> - Escaped block of text: &#60;![CDATA[ text ]]&#62;</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/Comment.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::Comment</a> - An XML comment: &#60;!-- comment --&#62;</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/EntityReference.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::EntityReference</a> - Refers to an ENTITY: &#38;ent; or %ent;</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/Entity.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::Entity</a> - An ENTITY definition: &#60;!ENTITY ...&#62;</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/ProcessingInstruction.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::ProcessingInstruction</a> - &#60;?PI target&#62;</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/DocumentFragment.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::DocumentFragment</a> - Lightweight node for cut &#38; paste</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/Notation.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::Notation</a> - An NOTATION definition: &#60;!NOTATION ...&#62;</li>
</ul>

<p>In addition, the XML::DOM module contains the following nodes that are not part of the DOM Level 1 Specification:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/ElementDecl.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::ElementDecl</a> - Defines an element: &#60;!ELEMENT ...&#62;</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/AttlistDecl.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::AttlistDecl</a> - Defines one or more attributes in an &#60;!ATTLIST ...&#62;</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/AttDef.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::AttDef</a> - Defines one attribute in an &#60;!ATTLIST ...&#62;</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/XMLDecl.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::XMLDecl</a> - An XML declaration: &#60;?xml version=&#34;1.0&#34; ...&#62;</li>
</ul>

<p>Other classes that are part of the DOM Level 1 Spec:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3ADOM%3A%3AImplementation" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::Implementation</a> - Provides information about this implementation. Currently it doesn&#39;t do much.</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/NodeList.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::NodeList</a> - Used internally to store a node&#39;s child nodes. Also returned by getElementsByTagName.</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/NamedNodeMap.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::NamedNodeMap</a> - Used internally to store an element&#39;s attributes.</li>
</ul>

<p>Other classes that are not part of the DOM Level 1 Spec:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/DOM/Parser.pod" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::Parser</a> - An non-validating XML parser that creates XML::DOM::Documents</li>

<li><a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3ADOM%3A%3AValParser" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::DOM::ValParser</a> - A validating XML parser that creates XML::DOM::Documents. It uses <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3AChecker" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Checker</a> to check against the DocumentType (DTD)</li>

<li><a href="/~tjmather/XML-DOM-1.44/lib/XML/Handler/BuildDOM.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Handler::BuildDOM</a> - A PerlSAX handler that creates XML::DOM::Documents.</li>
</ul>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="XML::DOM_package"
>XML::DOM package <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<dl>
<dt><a name='Constant'></a><a name="Constant_definitions"
>Constant definitions</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>The following predefined constants indicate which type of node it is.</p>
</dd>
</dl>

<pre class="sh_perl"> UNKNOWN_NODE (0)                The node type is unknown (not part of DOM)

 ELEMENT_NODE (1)                The node is an Element.
 ATTRIBUTE_NODE (2)              The node is an Attr.
 TEXT_NODE (3)                   The node is a Text node.
 CDATA_SECTION_NODE (4)          The node is a CDATASection.
 ENTITY_REFERENCE_NODE (5)       The node is an EntityReference.
 ENTITY_NODE (6)                 The node is an Entity.
 PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION_NODE (7) The node is a ProcessingInstruction.
 COMMENT_NODE (8)                The node is a Comment.
 DOCUMENT_NODE (9)               The node is a Document.
 DOCUMENT_TYPE_NODE (10)         The node is a DocumentType.
 DOCUMENT_FRAGMENT_NODE (11)     The node is a DocumentFragment.
 NOTATION_NODE (12)              The node is a Notation.

 ELEMENT_DECL_NODE (13)          The node is an ElementDecl (not part of DOM)
 ATT_DEF_NODE (14)               The node is an AttDef (not part of DOM)
 XML_DECL_NODE (15)              The node is an XMLDecl (not part of DOM)
 ATTLIST_DECL_NODE (16)          The node is an AttlistDecl (not part of DOM)

 Usage:

   if ($node-&#62;getNodeType == ELEMENT_NODE)
   {
       print &#34;It&#39;s an Element&#34;;
   }</pre>

<p><b>Not In DOM Spec</b>: The DOM Spec does not mention UNKNOWN_NODE and, quite frankly, you should never encounter it. The last 4 node types were added to support the 4 added node classes.</p>

